post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_32504090_32504155_0": {"length": 7, "quality": 0.7, "section_id": 5461}}, "n3337": {"so_32504090_32504155_0": {"length": 7, "quality": 0.7, "section_id": 5248}}, "n4659": {"so_32504090_32504155_0": {"length": 7, "quality": 0.7, "section_id": 6895}}}, "32504090": {"ViewCount": "155", "Body": "<p>When declaring an enum (class) I can specify the underlying type that the enum will use, e.g.</p>\n<pre><code>enum class MyEnum : baseType { FIRST, SECOND };\n</code></pre>\n<p>What can <code>baseType</code> be? The usual choice would be <code>uint32_t</code> or something similar but could it also be <code>float</code>? Or even my own class?</p>\n", "AcceptedAnswerId": "32504155", "Title": "What are the allowed types for an enum (class)?", "CreationDate": "2015-09-10T14:05:24.043", "Id": "32504090", "CommentCount": "0", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastActivityDate": "2015-09-10T14:18:29.657", "Score": "2", "OwnerUserId": "2746401", "Tags": "<c++><c++11><c++14>", "AnswerCount": "1"}, "32504155": {"Id": "32504155", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_32504090_32504155_0\"><code>N4140 [dcl.enum]/2:</code> [...] <strong>The type-specifier-seq of an enum-base shall name an integral type; any cv-qualification is ignored.</strong> [...]</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>So <code>baseType</code> can be any integral type, i.e. <code>bool</code>, <code>char</code>, <code>char16_t</code>, <code>char32_t</code>, <code>wchar_t</code> and the signed and unsigned integer types.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "496161", "LastActivityDate": "2015-09-10T14:18:29.657", "Score": "7", "CreationDate": "2015-09-10T14:07:52.330", "ParentId": "32504090", "CommentCount": "0", "OwnerUserId": "496161", "LastEditDate": "2015-09-10T14:18:29.657"}});